TY  - JOUR
AU  - Akerlof, George A.
AU  - Yellen, Janet L.
AU  - Katz, Michael L.
T1  - An Analysis of Out-of-Wedlock Childbearing in the United States*
PY  - 1996
Y1  - 1996/05/01
DO  - 10.2307/2946680
JO  - The Quarterly Journal of Economics
JA  - Q J Econ
VL  - 111
IS  - 2
SP  - 277
EP  - 317
SN  - 0033-5533
AB  - This paper relates the erosion of the custom of shotgun marriage to the legalization of abortion and the increased availability of contraception to unmarried women in the United States. The decline in shotgun marriage accounts for a significant fraction of the increase in out-of-wedlock first births. Several models illustrate the analogy between women who do not adopt either birth control or abortion and the hand-loom weavers, both victims of changing technology. Mechanisms causing female immiseration are modeled and historically described. This technology-shock hypothesis is an alternative to welfare and job-shortage theories of the feminization of poverty.
Y2  - 3/25/2024
UR  - https://doi.org/10.2307/2946680
ER  - 



